<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_04.gif"><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/clear.gif" height=35 width=1></td>
<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="...328fedb22570524062aeb1303" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php3'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Ophidian 2350</option><option value='/magic/treports/treports.php'>The Wastelands</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Keep Your Style Versatile!<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.88)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=4282'>Joshua "Stormcrow" Grace</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=4282&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> March 15, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> No, this isn&#39;t an article about A Ranger&#39;s Versatility. This is about YOUR versatility.<br />
<br />
When you go to a tournament, you should have already spent some time tweaking your deck, sorting through all your cards for just the right matches, picking out the chaff, and getting it ready to beat EVERYTHING. Right?<br />
<br />
Right. In fact, the only thing you shouldn&#39;t have accounted for were your actual games--how your deck draws and who and what types of decks you face.<br />
<br />
Certainly, better players all pay careful attention to the meta-game. If they suspect loads of Orcs and Conditions, they&#39;ll probably play Gandalf for Sleep, Caradhras. If they suspect a heavy contingent of Nazgul and Uruk-hai, they may opt to play toward a Ranger / Twilight denial, choking the opponents&#39; hands. But the meta-game is all odds and probability. It&#39;s not actual, not real. The truth is that you could be paired against a deck you&#39;re not as prepared to face.<br />
<br />
Now, your deck ought to have a chance, of some sort, against *all* decks. After all, you&#39;re there, in the game. But how do you teach your deck to play well against bad match-ups? You chose to play twilight denial, and you&#39;re facing your second Under the Watching Eye / Orc Bowmen deck of the day. A bad match-up since you have no way to kill conditions in your opponent&#39;s support area.<br />
<br />
So what do you do?<br />
<br />
Well, first of all, learn how to meta-game against the players at your level. If you expect to have a chance to win the tournament, meta-game against the top players. If you know, realistically, you&#39;re going to be in the middle of the pack, meta-game against those players. Meta-gaming might only be a game of odds, but when you play it right, it will work wonders for you.<br />
<br />
But by the time your opponent plays his first Orc Bowmen against your Rangers, it&#39;s a little late to re-meta-game. Sure, the first guy beat you, after his direct damage clinically picked off your characters, one by one, until they all died at site 8. But this time you&#39;ve got a plan...<br />
<br />
And learning how to formulate a plan, early, is everything...<br />
<br />
You&#39;ve learned since your early defeat that his orcs aren&#39;t going to kill you in skirmishes, but he needs to draw through his deck for those Under the Watching Eyes and Orc Bowmen. You&#39;re playing Twilight Denial, so he can&#39;t play too much against you each movement and, thus, can&#39;t get too many cards out of his hand during your movements. You&#39;ve learned enough to double-move each turn, limiting your opponent&#39;s ability to draw into those direct-damage cards. Sure, it&#39;s always wise to double-move when it&#39;s possible, but the key is that now you *know* you need to double-move, even if it&#39;s a little risky.<br />
<br />
My favorite example of overcoming an adverse situation by adapting play style was that when Durin&#39;s Bane became legal, I spent an evening trying to figure out how to keep my favorite deck tight and still get by the Balrog. I tried to find ways to fit in Boro-Rare and Armor, or Armor x2, or anything, really... But I kept finding out that any changes I made to the deck just watered it down, making it less effective on the whole, focusing too much on the threat of the Balrog. So, I stepped back and approached the problem differently. Since I was playing an archery deck with no Armors and limited characters, the worst thing (involving the Balrog) that could happen to me was that someone could drop an Uruk, Saruman&#39;s Snows, and then follow that up with the Balrog (the Little Bomb). Now, I was starting with Sam and Greenleaf in order to go first and pull Aragorn, drop Gandalf, and run. Because Sam was merely a burden monkey, I was killing him off ASAP. But as I thought about it, I realized that Sam was the answer to my problem. If I just kept him alive until site 5 and kept Gandalf at one wound or less, I could sacrifice him to the Balrog and take the fierce hit with Gandalf. I&#39;d just adjusted my deck for the new meta-game without making any card changes.<br />
<br />
Of course, you adapt not only with your Fellowship side, but with your Shadow side as well. Learning to dump extra minions against a Twilight Denial deck in favor of the cheaper events and conditions can be a key adaptation. Your deck needs to be balanced before you start playing any given game, but using that balance to the best effect is a matter of adapting to the game as it progresses.<br />
<br />
Here, then, are some general guidelines to adapting during your games:<br />
<br />
1. Adapting your objectives. You should know if you want to go first or second based on your overall objective. You want to go first if you want to win the race. Starting in second will most frequently keep you in second, and by site 9, second is the loser. If your objective is to overwhelm your opponent&#39;s Frodo, it frequently helps to go second, allowing you to play another turn of minions, cycling your hand, before you move--this also tends to put a few more shadow cards into your opponent&#39;s hand and, therefore, a few less resources to deal with your shadow. As you go through the tournament, you&#39;ll learn to bid higher if there aren&#39;t decks that punish burdens and to bid conservatively if there are. You&#39;ll learn whether or not you should be bidding to try to win the race or to overwhelm your opponent.<br />
<br />
2. Playing and drawing cards. This is, of course, the most obvious way you can adapt while actually in a game. Usually, dropping cards to draw cards at every opportunity is good. But it pays to know which cards to drop. And, sometimes, you just can&#39;t afford to discard. If you find yourself losing in the race (or in danger of being overwhelmed), it can be good to drop Free Peoples cards in the hope that you might overwhelm your opponent&#39;s Frodo. If you find yourself in the lead, it might be good to draw for Free Peoples cards for the double-move as much as possible, forcing your opponent to run to keep up. However, there are times, too, where you&#39;ll want to get rid of *everything* in your hand to draw for the cards you know will be key to your success. At these times, people praise They Are Coming and Gwemegil for the adaptability and card-drawing advantage they offer. You&#39;ll note that Gwemegil will let you discard 2 cards to increase Arwen&#39;s strength--and that isn&#39;t to a maximum of 1 strength higher than a minion&#39;s--that&#39;s to a maximum of the cards in your hand. So, just assign Arwen to a skirmish and dump cards like crazy to draw more.<br />
<br />
3. Learning your opponent. This is almost an article of its own (and has been mentioned in at least a couple of other articles), but your ability to learn your opponent&#39;s &quot;give aways&quot; and to bluff, yourself, will give you a slight measure of control beyond the cards themselves.<br />
<br />
4. Who dies? And when? Before you go to a tournament, you should know which of your characters are expendable. Ulitmately, all but the Ringbearer. But some will be more important as the games progress. Is Aragorn your only Ranger for your 3 Versatilities? He might be important, then. Try to keep him out of close-call situations as those have a habit of turning bad. Is your opponent playing Sauron? Well, try to exert characters so that you have more than one health left for each of your important characters. Sauron Orcs have a tendency of Hating away your guys. Playing Uruk-hai? You&#39;ll need to know how to schedule your wounds and when to expect those nastuy strength-enhancing events (or discarded Saruman&#39;s Ambitions) that Uruk are famous for.<br />
<br />
5. Have fun. You can strategize until the cows come home, but sometimes things just won&#39;t go your way. Or sometimes you&#39;ll end up crushing not only your opponent&#39;s Fellowship, but his spirit as well. Learn how to relax when the game is lopsided. Give up gracefully if you can&#39;t win; play out the game looking for a Heroic death. Or if you&#39;re going to pummel your opponent, make a story out of it. Make it fun.<br />
<br />
Walk with Eru,<br />
Joshua &quot;Stormcrow&quot; Grace <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?id=3467&view=1&PHPSESSID=...328fedb22570524062aeb1303'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?PHPSESSID=...328fedb22570524062aeb1303'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php?PHPSESSID=...328fedb22570524062aeb1303'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
